food: The Hyderabadi fish fry had a crispy crust and was perfectly seasoned with the traditional masalas.
The mutton keema samosas were crunchy on the outside, filled with a spicy, flavorful keema mixture.
The chicken biryani was fragrant and spicy, with tender pieces of chicken perfectly infused with the spices.
Kebabs from the old city were perfectly grilled, smoky, and juicy, served with naan and mint chutney.
The Hyderabadi chicken kebab had a tender texture with spices that lingered just the right amount.
The Hyderabadi mutton korma was rich, creamy, and full of bold flavors, a true Hyderabad signature dish.
The raan (whole leg of mutton) was roasted to perfection with a tender, smoky flavor that was irresistible.
The tandoori chicken was perfectly marinated, charred just right, and had a deep smoky flavor.
Mutton do pyaaza was loaded with caramelized onions and rich flavors, an authentic Hyderabadi treat.
The mutton biryani was an explosion of flavors, every grain of rice was infused with spices, and the mutton was so tender.
Hyderabadi chicken curry had a rich gravy, the chicken was juicy and cooked perfectly in the spicy broth.
The mutton seekh kebabs were grilled to perfection with a crispy outer layer and juicy, tender meat inside.
The Hyderabadi chicken shawarma was packed with flavor, with perfectly seasoned chicken and soft pita bread.
Nihari was hearty and satisfying, the tender beef fell apart with a fork and was rich with aromatic spices.
Mutton raan was tender and juicy, the spices deeply infused, making it a perfect dish for a special occasion.
The Hyderabadi gosht ka salan was spicy and tangy, a great complement to the fluffy biryani.
The tandoori chicken was perfectly charred, smoky, and flavorful with a wonderful balance of spices.
The Hyderabadi chicken biryani had an impeccable balance of spices, and the chicken was incredibly soft and juicy.

The chicken pakoda had a crispy golden coating with succulent chicken pieces inside, flavored to perfection.
The Hyderabadi mutton korma had an aromatic, rich gravy that paired beautifully with naan and rice.

The chicken tandoori was smoky, juicy, and had the perfect amount of spice, leaving a delightful aftertaste.
Hyderabadi gosht biryani was layered with tender pieces of meat and perfectly cooked rice, an absolute treat
